The `Config` struct holds an owned reference to `owner`, so each instance owns its own copy. The compiler error you see is: "cannot move out of `owner` because it is a reference" – you’re trying to assign the same borrowed value into two different structs.
```rust
type Config {
    owner: String,
    data: i32,
}
fn main(){
    let cfg = Config{owner:"alice",data:42};
    // you cannot do this in a loop:
    for _ in 0..10 {
        let _cfg = cfg.clone();
    }
}
```
Here cloning creates duplicate ownership, which is fine as long as each instance owns its own data.

If the error persists, maybe you have a reference to a `String` that outlives the struct.

Because the function takes `self` (a struct) and holds an immutable reference to `owner`. If the caller is holding a mutable reference elsewhere, the borrow checker blocks it. The error message is: "cannot borrow `self.owner as &mut Self::owner`: the value does not live long enough".
```rust
type Config {
    owner: String,
    data: i32,
}
fn update_owner(cfg: &Config, new_name: &str) -> Result<Self, &'static str> {
    cfg.owner = new_name.to_owned(); // mutable borrow allowed
    Ok(cfg)
}
// This fails if you have a mutable reference elsewhere:
let mut owner_ref = cfg; // error[E0382]
```
To fix it, either make the function take `&mut Config` or ensure no other mutable references exist.

Add a lifetime parameter `L` to the struct: `type Config<'a> { owner: &'a str, data: i32 }`. Then both functions refer only to `'a`‑borrowed strings. The code becomes:
```rust
type Config<'a> {
    owner: &'a str,
    data: i32,
}
fn get_owner(c: &Config<'_>) -> Option<&'a str> { Some(&c.owner) }

fn set_owner(mut c: Config<'_>, new: &str) -> Config<'_> {
    c.owner = new;
    c
}
```
Now the compiler accepts:
`let cfg = Config::new("alice", 42); let _ = get_owner(&cfg); let cfg2 = set_owner(cfg, "bob");`

